< Review>
I've been frequenting this barber shop for years, years before they called it New York cuts.  It's true what that kid said in his review.   Their friends are allowed to cut in line, you sit there wait and your the next customer in line, but then the ref raft walks in and you become number 5 inline.  They also have a habit of funneling us to the barber that can't cut hair.  Out of respect I'm not going to point any fingers but there are barbers that been there for years that can't cut hair.   At time they have barbers that are just starting off without a license cutting hair and of course they'll try to funnel you to those barbers.  Bottom line, there's a few barbers that are better than excellent and the few that just can't cut it.  Those are the barbers they try funneling us strangers or none friends to.</Review>

< Text>
Went in, by mistake, during their Friends and Family Night, January 25th. Despite my mistake, I was greeted by one one the owners (Judy). She welcomed me to their store with open arms, despite my mishap, and gave her employees a bit of a live training experience.
To give a bit of a run-down, the owners have been in the cannabis industry for 10 years, offering them a great deal of experience in the ever-changing regulations of cannabis.
The store reflects the experience, too. With a large, open lobby and plenty of space in the showroom, this dispensary boasts a large capacity for any kind of rush as well as a full, knowledgeable staff to handle it.
With enough support and luck, this store has potential to be one of Seaside's greatest.</Text>

<Time>1556141783659<//Time><Rate>5<//Rate><review>In my opinion this is the best dispensary we have in the 831. And not that i had negative experiences at other places, but hear me out.  First and foremost everyone is extremely helpful including the "security guard". I put that in quotes, because he's more of a greeter than some required hand by the county/state. You can tell this guy enjoys his job and is part of the Plantacea family and not some dude out front checking IDs. And he ALWAYS has a smile on his face!  Then you have the people working the counter, once again always smiling, offering you a beverage or treats from the the snacky snack table. They are also very knowledgeable about the products and helpful.

I have very simple needs when i visit a dispensary. I don't need 50 different types of flower, extracts, wax, shatter and all that other fancy stuff youngins be consuming these days. Although if you have needs for something stronger to cure what ails you, they got it.  With that said, the selection here is more than adequate and everything I've ever purchased has been excellent.  The cost is on par with other places except, If You're Local! Anyone residing in Monterey County (I think County) gets 20% OFF ALL DAY EVERY DAY. Hard to beat that. First time visit for non-local I believe is 20% Off, but don't quote me on that.

The facility itself kinda reminds me of an Apple store minus the pretentious douche-baggery. Clean, spacious  and lots of big portraits covering wall space. And yes, people in portraits are smiling too. Portraits almost look like stock photography, because everyone is so photogenic, but i was told they are customers. Well, i think they need some ugly people on the wall to make it more local and realistic. I volunteered myself to be that ugly portrait and shared my grievance with the staff. Hopefully this makes its way to upper management, because i'm ready for my glamour photo shoot when you guys are.

If you're looking for a dispensary that treats you like family, i highly recommend Plantacea. The customer service far exceeds the competition and promise you wont be disappointed.<//review>< Pictures>
None</Pictures>

Update: After posting our review I was contacted by JC, the General Manager. He apologized for the delay in getting our refund and sent a check out the same day. He assured me they are working on training their management to handle these situations in a much more timely manner. We will give them another shot and we are hopeful we will not have the same problem in the future. I have removed the 1 star review and changed it to 3 star. Will update again in the future after we buy a few more products from them.

We have used this company for our Resale parts in the past and have had no problem. However, this last experience has shown us that this company does not have integrity and does not stand behind their products or their word. On July 6th we ordered a power steering gear box from them. When we received the part one of our mechanics installed it and it immediately blew power steering fluid out, all over everything. We called Performance Online Customer Service and advised them that the part had faulty seals and requested a call tag to send back the product. Rich in customer service said we would need to send the part back at our own expense so they could see that the product was in fact defective, and that then they would issue a refund for the part AND the shipping. We shipped the part back on 7/20/18 and got confirmation that it was received on 7/26/18 by Jordan. We started calling the next week to inquire about our refunds. I had to make at least 10 phone calls to try and get someone to handle this refund. I finally was put in touch with their manager Rick Evans whom assured me he had this handled and that we would receive the refund for the part and the shipping fees which were $47.00. After several phone calls with Rick I began emailing him on August 20th almost a month AFTER they had received the part back. We still had not received any money back.  On August 21st  after contacting Rick again He emailed me that our refunds were scheduled to be processed on August 24th.  They did process the refund for the part on this day but neglected to process the shipping fees refund. Once again, I contacted Rick who assured me they would be refunded but that they needed time to ‚Äúfigure out‚Äù how to refund the money. I was told that the accounting department was contacting the owner to figure out how to facilitate the refund. On September 11th after several more emails, Rick sent an email apologizing and saying he thought it had been taken care of (even though I had sent several emails to the contrary which were ignored). It is now September 24th , 2 months after they received the part back and I still have not received our shipping fees we paid to send back a defective part. This has cost us much more than the shipping cost. We had time in cleaning up the mess the defective seal caused, we had to replace the power steering fluid, we had to pay our mechanic to do the job twice and have spent way too much time trying to collect a refund from a company on a defective part they sold. We know a defective part can happen and don‚Äôt fault the company for that, but the horrible customer service that we have received is on them. We purchase a lot of resale parts for our shop and will no longer purchase any parts from them.  I caution anyone else from doing so unless you want to spend countless hours trying to recover your refund. This company does not stand behind their product or their word without an exhaustive amount of follow-up.</review>

A TRUE ZERO STARS COMPANY!

We spent about $3,200 at POL, or as we now refer to them, POS, as that is much more fitting to describe their parts and service. We purchased a front disc brake conversion kit for a 1964 Chevy Pickup as well as power steering conversion and other stuff. We had NOTHING BUT PROBLEMS with the horrible product they have slapped together in China and then passed on to customers and they simply don't care. Parts were missing, broken, or not calibrated correctly from the get go. We are over an hour drive from the Performance Online "Showroom" and have made that long trek more times than we care to admit to exchange parts. We had to exchange the brake booster 3 times for product failure, master cylinder twice, proportioning valve once and STILL the product was junk and failed again and again.

In the end, to resolve the brake issues, we had to replace BOTH calipers with stock GM replacement parts from O'Reilly Auto. We also replaced the brake booster and check valve with a stock replacement from O'Reilly. After over a year of dealing with the uncaring, unsympathetic people at POL, we knew we had to replace the junk they sold us and do it ourselves to have a reliable brake system in our vehicle. I am not even going to delve into how many calls were not returned, rude advice, or the months it took to get a refund from exchanging parts via mail.

Brakes are not an optional feature on a vehicle and their failure due to inferior parts is very serious. Luckily no one got hurt, but we sure learned a lesson and will NEVER BUY POS FROM POL AGAIN and at every show, we be sure to warm other car and truck enthusiasts to STAY AWAY!

As for the company's response saying I never purchased the brake conversions from them, we did. They wrote it up in my wife's name (different last name) and YES, I STILL have the complete receipt to prove it! I lived local at the time and drove there to pick it up for my birthday to save on freight charges. Nice try, but your service and products really are that bad!</review>

We are very sorry for them not being honest with us and have had many discussions with our manufacturer about their level of customer service. We apologize to Mr. Hernandez for this situation.'}<//resp>

I came here based on great reviews but I just had a not so great experience. It was only myself and one other person in the shop and honestly I wasn't pleased with the quality of my $30 pedicure (tech scrubbed then left scrub on and applied mask treatment right over it). The basic pedicure is advertised outside as $19.99, but the pedicure "B" that I got was $30. Not a very good special for a first time customer.  Overall the salon is not very clean either. the corners and under the nail drying table and bathroom, need a good sweep, wipe down and mopping. And lastly, the nail tech that completed my manicure applied a gel top coat instead of the regular top coat that is needed for my regular polish manicure. I told her that the bottle says gel top coat, but she said "no, we refilled the bottle with regular top coat". After 5 min of slimy top coated nails, she told the other 2 techs the problem and sure enough she had to remove all polish and re-polish and top coat my nails! Maybe it's an off day, maybe I'm too picky, but for $42, I've had way better service at Alhambra Nails and at La Fleur nail salons. I will not be returning here again.:(</text>

<time>1597460324376< /time>< Text>
This place has tremendous potential. Being said, it just isn't there yet.

Sashimi - so sad to see delicious cuts of fish splayed out on top of cucumber that takes away from the taste. Cucumber was all I could taste, which was disappointing as I order sashimi for the great fish. Also, the cuts of fish were the strangest I've ever seen for sashimi (cut at weird angles, in weird shapes).

Ceviche - fine, the best we had in the meal. It could be better without the noodles(?) underneath the fish, just doesn't fit into the dish (being said, I'm fully aware I ordered ceviche at a Japanese food place).

Rolls - massive slices, heavy on the rice. I'd personally like to see ~ 75% of each cut, and much less rice.

I see where the restaurant is going and appreciate it. Looking forward to hopefully trying again on another pass.</Text>

<review>I came in on Sunday about 2pm. There was a small wait but the cashier cleared the line fairly quick. We scoped out the buffet line (a variety of 5 small pizzas, and salad bar). I must say this place is expensive. We ordered an extra large (16 slices) of half supreme, half pepperoni/sausage, 12 twists, and 12 wings. Total came out to about 60 bucks. The oven must be turned on a lil high because the twists came out a little too done, and the crust on the pizza was extra crispy, not by request either. The twists could use a little more cheese on the inside. Pizza was ok, a ton of red sauce on it, which helped the dry crust. The pepperoni side was dry, but the supreme side was pretty satisfying. I've had better at other Round Tables. Kind of disappointed in the pizza here compared to others. I usually love Round Table Pizza, not so much this one, but I just moved here and I was excited since its closeby. Wings were good too. The table was clean but sticky. Even tho the dine in area was dead, except for us there, the staff was pretty slow on cleaning up the tables. There was a young female working, she seemed very responsible, courteous, and cared about the job. She didn't even serve us, that's just what I observed while dining in. There were 2 young guys working as well, the one that served us seemed less enthusiastic about the job, and lazy. Tall, skinny kid. There are 3 big tv's in the main dining area, and 1 in the side dining area. There are also booster seats for kids, wheelchair accessible tables. Overall, it was an ok experience. If there was another Round Table closeby or even a bit further I would probably go to that one instead.< /review>< pictures>

Luis P.</username>
<date>1374879997478<//date>< Rating>
4</Rating>
<Review>What happens when you mix an old and tried pizza recipe with a crew of young, energetic-want to please, staff? Answer: A not too shabby choice for the incredibly popular world of pizza. It seems that everyone and their cousins is running a pizzeria business, and they use key words like New York Style, Chicago, 900 degree ovens, and of course they can not all be the very best. No disrespect here, but I am sure that anyone who owns a business has to say they are outstanding, but are they really? Then you must see reviews, the more the merrier because it eliminates the possibility that personal relations, friends or family, are exaggerating the quality overall.
So if one is an avid food searcher in the area in which they reside or live, they will have to spend hard earned cash to find out the plain truth.
Enter Round Table Pizza in Temecula. First time visit, used to like Round Table years back. We knew it was chain, but somehow placed Round Table above the avid corporate competitors: Pizza Hut, Domino's, Papa Johns, Little Ceaser's, Papa Murphy's (in a smaller scale and slightly better, perhaps, than the other names mentioned?). We enter at 4:30 PM and were greeted by a fine young employee by the name of Cody, who also made the pizza for us. I asked about specials. He said a large Hawaiian style pizza for $16.95, as opposed to $23.95 regular price? I do not fancy pineapple as a norm, but it sounded good with pineapple, bacon bits, canadian bacon, red onion, green onion, tomato, and an overly sweet sauce which was not the traditional red sauce, it made the pizza at times taste like too sweet. Plus a free small serving of fresh jalape√±os. Nice and accommodating, this Cody.  3 small drinks free refills (which none was used for the soda machine lacked carbonation and tasted the drinks tasted like heavy syrup-quality control issue-that made a strong case for staying away from sodas altogether, anyhow).
Pizza arrived piping hot, us being the only clientele at that time but phones seemed to have started ringing for their delivery, at the hands of Cody, the Baker. The presentation was awesome! Cody had excelled in his preparation of this pie, and I do not say that lightly, for one time I went to Pizzeria Ortica in the expensive South Coast Plaza area in Costa Mesa, where each individual size pie is around $18? Considered the vedette of the pizza world theirs arrived at our table wish so little of anything, that the dough was the only thing to be sure of. It is considered in this expensive, gourmet world that less is in reality, more. How they came out with such a notion I will never know, for I always say the more the merrier, you conceited over expensive pizza joint!
Round Table's pizza was perfect in that sense. Plenty of everything, with not one topping overcoming the others. Flavor got old fast (unless you are an strict Hawaiian pizza lover, and like the sweetness of putting canned pineapple-and yes, perhaps, also the sweet juice? on it), many are liable to grow tired like we did. The crust was very tasty (heads up, Ortica!), with a crunchiness worth noting. The dough perhaps a little wet on top, but barely.
Presented with a proud smile, we could not help but to compare Cody's attitude with the many arrogant ones alone the way, he would not conceal the fact that this pizza was his creation! That's how I do it, now what! We love a proud cook, for we know we can expect the best, prefer them tenfold to the dormant-going through the motions type-that is for sure!
The toppings, specially the fresh ones in the produce department, were al dente and perfectly implemented. The bacon bits nothing special out of the box, kind of like artificial, box in which they come. Canadian Bacon much nicer. Overall, paying $25 out the door was not too shabby.
Nice crew, Cody a revelation of sorts on his intense preparation of our pizza-almost like if anyone goes there might come in handy to ask for him. Nice people, average pizza, nice value. 4 Stars.< /Review><Pics>None<//Pics>< Resp>
None< /Resp>

1612146039712</date>
<rating>5< /rating>< Review>
Since I arrive to San Diego every body is been talking to the pizza California stile! Been trying some places and then a friend told me about Pizza Port.

Highly recommend, for my is the best Pizza in San Diego, we just try the cheese pizza, thanks to my kids, but is really good !

This is also a brewery in San Diego and they have a very good beer, the one that I love is Shark Bite brown ale!! Awesome!

The staff were really friendly!!

Good work guys!!<//Review>

<Rating>5< /Rating><Review>The beer is some of the best in San Diego, which is a high compliment in this beer town. The pizza is also really good. There are a lot of pizzas, including several veggie options. You can also get it normal or thin crust style. The service is friendly. It's counter service, not table service, which feels especially good in these covid times. <user>112402214680656830849< /user><response>None< /response>< rating>
5< /rating>
<pictures>None</pictures>< Review>
Delicious pizza and suds! We beat the Sunday crowd by getting there at 5pm. It was busy by 6pm, but the food came out quick enough for us, but appetizers helped. There's a food only line on the right. Food and brew line to the left. Ask for samples of their brews.
Pizza was nice and doughy, but not thick like pan pizza, not too thin either. Loads of toppings!!!
The Carlsbad was outstanding... hope you like artichoke, pesto and fetaüòâ. BBQ cheeseburger had meatballs, not ground beef, I liked it more than I thought I would. I was expecting weird, but the meatballs made it seem more traditional.
Wings were baked, not bready. (The way i like it)
We got the veggie basket as a side, it was ideal for a family of 4 or two really hungry people.
For you beer bodies, they offer cans, growlers, and 6 packs to go.
There's a small parking lot adjacent and there's a pay to park across the street. If you want free parking, plan on street parking and walking a block or two.< /Review>

<text>Killer pizza! This place does not disappoint. Dropped in with a group of college friends who were staying in Ocean Beach.

Pizza Port has a very chilled, laid-back vibe. We were quickly able to find a long table that accommodated our group. Note, that the tables are shared, so don't be afraid to chat up your neighbor.

Pizza took about 35 mins to bake, and we enjoyed few rounds of beer while waiting, along with the jalapeno poppers (highly recommend!). We tried the Garlic Veggie Pizza w/ traditional crust. Super fresh veggies and gooey cheese.

We will defiantly be back on our next trip to SD!<//text>< Pictures>

< Text>
I have been a fan of Pizza Port for many years. They keep the menu simple with pizza, salad, breadsticks, mozzarella sticks, and buffalo chicken wings and craft beer and soda and iced tea. I love all their food and they have lunch specials, like two slices and a drink or a slice, salad, and a beverage (non-alcoholic), and a couple other options. You can substitute a beer for an additional charge. They have the proper social distancing protocols on keeping your mask on when you are not seated at your table. You have to ask for napkins, utensils, parmesan cheese, or red pepper flakes.
The service is friendly and helpful. I fully recommend this Pizza Port in Ocean Beach, San Diego.
The toughest part about the Ocean Beach (OB) location is parking is scarce. Especially with the social distancing protocols in place, they took over the small 7 parking spot lot for outdoor dining.< /Text>

----------------Editted a few months later-----------------

Edit: From five to three stars for super rude staff. First I tried to order slices and the bartender told me they weren't doing slices so I ordered two small pizzas. Before my order came up I watched several people order and pick up individual slices. So I then had two small pizzas and needed some to-go boxes. They normally have them sitting out to help yourself. They didn't have any available so I requested two boxes from the staff. The busser said to me "two boxes? Why do you need two boxes?" I explained I had two pizzas but he retorted with "uh huh." I allowed my -well over 21- boyfriend to sample my beer (he didn't want one but wanted to try it) and we had the busser inform us that he couldn't taste my drink without getting ID'ed by the bartender and then said if he saw it again he would "have to bounce us". Asking for an ID would have sufficed. He absolutely did not need to treat us like we were breaking the law. This is a brewery, you have to assume people will sample each other's drinks. It's not accepted to threaten to remove someone from the property over it without requesting an ID first.

I don't know if they were recently hit with a fine or what but this behavior is a little wild. This place has been a favorite of ours for years and the entire atmosphere totally flipped. I hope that this trend doesn't continue because it makes it extremely uncomfortable to dine and relax.<//Text><user_name>Dani Vierra<//user_name></record>

<date>1528700948747< /date><Gmap_id>0x80deaa3a261cd2e3:0x3e89464c53bf352< /Gmap_id><rating>5</rating><UserId.>114054506485824647528<//UserId.>< response>

< Name>
Garrett Bredell< /Name>
<Review>Pizza Port's OB location is a staple for every one of my visits to the area. It captures the spirit of the area so well - surf, beer, and a loose and casual feel. Just a little off the main drag, it's within easy reach for tired surfers and rubbernecks alike, and makes a fine choice when Hodad's is running a line around the corner.

First, I've really only had the pizza. And it's good, competing with NY Slice style pizza around San Diego (East Coasters might turn their nose up at the place, FWIW.) I've also sampled the kale salad which was inappropriately healthy given the settings. The real treat here is the beer, which is always diverse, experimental, affordable, and delicious. Pizza Port's social media game has been overshadowed by newer players, but the brewing and taste is still on point, and matches supremely with the pizza available.

Head in during the lunch special and get away with two slices and a beer for less than $10, then get back to the beach with your newly acquired gut. Or return to the main street and go shopping, if you can resist the temptation to nap.</Review>< pics>
[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNfrX949lJWoaprOxcwitwpuLNv859ZUvAvRiWj=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pics>

<date>1595603547862<//date>< Text>
WARNING: Do NOT place orders via ChowNow.

I've been a regular at the OB and Solana Beach Pizza Port locations since childhood.

Yesterday, I placed an order online for pickup at the OB Pizza Port via ChowNow.  I arrived 15 minutes after receiving the notification that the food was ready.  Due to an error between the shop and ChowNow, my order was never received so I waited for it to be prepared (outside, standing on the curb due to COVID restrictions) after being quoted 15 minutes.  30 minutes later, I checked on the progress and was informed that I had been made the incorrect pizza and that they would finish the one I ordered in 10 minutes.  One hour after I initially arrived to pick up my food, I finally received what I ordered.

The women who served me were very kind and offered the incorrectly-made pizza for free in addition to what I ordered, which I really appreciated.  Unfortunately, because I had to wait an hour to receive my order, my girlfriend missed a seminar she needed to attend.  Going forward, I unfortunately won't be providing my business to the OB location.<//Text>

<UserId.>102688869887787648484</UserId.><Review>It was okay. I was disappointed because I took my kids here SPECIFICALLY to have some of their house-made root beer and when I ordered it, was told that the machine was broken. Oddly enough, that was the same story I got when I visited the Solana Beach location a couple of years ago. Regardless, if they're not going to offer an item, I think that the menu board should note that it's not available. Also, I ordered the lunch special and when I told the clerk what type of pizza I wanted, she replied that the only options were cheese, pepperoni, or the pizza of the day. The menu board says "any slice pizza" - again, if it's only certain types of pizza that are available with the special, then the menu should note that, not say "Any." I ordered the pizza of the day and it was yummy. It was hot and fresh, and the servings were large. The orders came out in a reasonable amount of time. If you're not a regular, it's a little unclear what you're supposed to do after you're finished eating - bus your own table? Leave it there? Some signage would help with that too. All in all, it was an ok experience. I wouldn't drive out of my way to go there again (like I did this time) and circle the block again & again looking for parking, but if I was already in the area, I'd eat there.< /Review>< Pictures>

109292797534330207421</user_id>
<username>Ruger Carstens</username><Time>1576209223993< /Time>< Rating>
5</Rating>
< text>
Fantastic, absolutely fantastic! So many delicious pizza options and a beer menu that goes on for days, what more could you ask for?

Went here for the first time for dinner with a group of co-workers. Ordered the Pizza Lahaina, Pizza Laguna, and Pizza San Clemente (love the pizzas named after California beaches). Each pizza was more scrumptious than the next! I never would have believed that a pizza with black bean sauce as its base could be so good but it was a revelation. My favorite was the Lahaina, but I'm one of those people who likes pineapple on a pizza with Canadian bacon.

Great, laid-back atmosphere at this place. The next time I'm in San Diego, Pizza Port will be on the short-list of places to go!<//text>

Beer, beer, and more beer.   And by the way they have pizza too! We went here For a birthday celebration. We ordered about five pizzas which were all gourmet ranging from a vegetarian option to a garlic and meat combination.  There were games for the kids to play while we socialized with the adults. < review>
The best Pizza Port location. It can get packed, but there is a good flow to the place, so it's never a problem. The pizza is one of the best in San Diego. My favorite is the veggie with added grilled chicken. Recently tried a specialty sausage and jalapeno that was impressive as well. The selection of beers never disappoints. < text>
Great for a crowd. Went for a birthday party with a group of six. We ordered individually and ordered too much food. Medium pies are quite large. They offer many different preset pizza options along with a create your own. We had the Mac and Cheese bites to start and they were good. Lots of video games and entertainment for the kids. Also a craft brewery on the premise. Very laid back experience. Order at the window and they call out your name to pick up the order. The announcer took some liberties with his announcements and created some smiles. Would go back with a crowd. Would not go by myself.</text>

1470587551502</Time>
< text>
Located near the beach, offers a great selection of Pizza Port beer along with other regional craft beer to go with a ton of pizza offerings... what's not to love?  The lunch special is a great way to go, but for the life of me I can't figure out the how/why of the additional $2 charge to add a beer to the meal as this only gives you a $2 discount when you go to the beer counter to get your beer.  So I've paid the $2 add on for my pizza salad to get a beer then get a $2 discount?  Why not just pay full price for my beer and save a step.

Anyway, the pizza, salad, and beer really hit the spot and provided a great base to build on for a full day of brewery hopping!  Would definitely go back.< /text>

Good Pizza, beer, people, and a pinball machine.  What more can you ask for? On weekend evenings are very crowded, but lunchtime is not that bad.  They have a good lunch special, a slice, and salad; both are HUGE. Big enough for sharing if you are not so hungry. <Rating>5< /Rating><date>1561488796531<//date><username>Jessica Nettles</username>< Text>
Once again, while looking for pizza we found this place and just the pictures of the food alone brought us into Pizza Port on a Saturday afternoon.  We came with our 3 children, and while I wouldn't necessarily call it a "family restaurant" I was comfortable with my two youngest being there because it's a loud, upbeat place where their noise levels would bother no one.
It took a few minutes to decide what we wanted, but we had an order of buffalo wings, which were dry rub and not super saucy, so they were good.  My littlest two each had slices of their favorite pizzas and the hubby and I each got a small, he had the San Clemente, and I the margherita pizza.  The individual slices were insane, they were bigger than the plates they were on.  The San Clemente has a black bean sauce, and it had this unique flavor that made me think I was eating somewhere between a taco and a pizza...it was quite good.  Then of course there was the Margherita pizza.  Not the best one I have ever had, but it was good and I would eat it again.   Truth be told though, I tasted the San Clemente first and it was so flavorful and yummy that maybe my tastebuds were a little screwy and the Margherita was just plain at that point.
We also enjoyed a Beer Float, something we'd discussed trying many many times, but had never actually come across.  We did at Pizza Port, and the options for beers in my float were amazing.  I went with a coffee porter and was pleasantly surprised.  Not gonna lie, I was skeptical, but I came out of this experience a fan.
This location is good for an afternoon slice and a cold beer or two.  Bringing the kids is totally fine, and going without them is totally fine too.
The atmosphere is laid back, the food is good, and the beer is cold.  What more could you ask for?< /Text>

<rate>1<//rate>< Review>
The pizza and beer may or may not be great, but I will rate the place 1 star because they advertise slices and apparently do not sell them all day. I walked in around 7pm and waited in line as I saw slices priced on the menu board.  I ordered 2 slices and a beer.  I was told "we don't sell slices until 9pm".  I said you have to be kidding.  I was told "we don't sell slices after 3pm". It all worked out though as I went down a couple blocks and had an excellent burger, rings and a beer at a super friendly shop around the corner.  As far as this place goes... I will get my slices elsewhere.</Review>

Came here after hearing mixed reviews from friends, and it was alright. Plenty of beer options, friendly staff overall, but the pizza was ehh. Good size slices, but very thin and greasy. <Resp>None< /Resp>< text>
Pizza Port is always poppin'. I drove by it 100s of times while living in Cardiff by the Sea. It's packed at lunch and dinner. They make their own beer there too. Try the honey beer. It's full of awesomeness.

It's kid friendly and has video game arcades too. The only thing I didn't like too much about it is the lack of seating available, but I guess that's what happens when you get great pizza and beer.

You basically order your pizza at the register and find a seat as fast as someone stands up. They will call your name over the loud speaker. No waiters here. Lots of fun. There is also another location (i think in Ocean Beach).<//text>

<text>Great spot but be prepared for a crowd and lots of kids.  The tables are pretty close together and it was a little difficult for me to transfer from my wheelchair to a bench seat but thats not the restaurants fault, it's the fault of the able-bodied family sitting at the only handicap accessible table. The employees are friendly and the pizza was stupid good. Great spot for a slice or a whole pie if you are in a group.  They do have a gluten free option for the crust but it's $3 more for those of you in need a GF option. < Text>
It's hard to write anything bad about this place since it already has a winning combination of pizza and beer. Add a killer location (Ocean Beach) to the list, and you've got the recipe for a great afternoon or evening out.

If I were to say anything negative about the joint, is it's a bit crowded. Don't expect to come to Pizza Port and get a private table for two. All seating is community style, and the place is loud... so be in the mood to be social! And if you aren't, just have a pitcher of beer and you'll be adding to the noise level in no time :-)< /Text>

< Text>
Really nice vibe here at PIzza Port. People are rough around the edges but overall pretty friendly. More often that not, every time I'm there, somehow another person's pizza slice ends up on my plate. It's strange but I don't fight it. Neither do the high number of dogs that can be found here during and after hours.

Also... they have big buck hunter. You're likely able to find many of the local 25 yr olds cocking shotguns and high-fiving while pounding wings on a wednesday night. Good vibes, although PP wing's have slowly slipped down hill like the arizona frat boys at nobes on a saturday.</Text>

<user>105929644731397610584</user><Name>Douglas LeClair< /Name><time>1412382964574<//time><Rating>5</Rating>< text>
I give Pizza Port 5 stars for the beer and 4 stars for the food. However I have a lot of non-craft beer drinking friends that come here just for the food, so my standards might be high. To me the pizza is the perfect complement to their beer - doughy, cheesy and loaded with toppings. Their beers are very underrated compared to other breweries in San Diego, mostly because they make so many that aren't all world-class. But all of them are above average, priced fairly, and served fresh from the brewery in a casual family-friendly environment. Frequently Pizza Port creates some beers that really knock it out of the park (Santa's Little Helper, Mongo IPA, Bacon & Eggs Breakfast Coffee Porter, etc.) They have a generous amount of taps devoted to "guest brewery beers" including Russian River, Ballast Point, etc. Their homemade root beer is awesome, I recommend trying a float. Or try some of their "beer buddies" which is cooked pizza dough bites brushed with garlic butter.</text>

<UserId.>113897371292918169007<//UserId.><Name>Ian - Fr0wnZ< /Name>< Date>

< rating>
4</rating>
<text>Came in with a group of friends for our last meal during our San Diego trip. Most of the group heard great things about Pizza Port, so it had to be a clear winner? Parking can be an issue with limited spots available, but luckily we found street parking about a block away.

The atmosphere of the restaurant looked fun and inviting. There were many flat screen TV's around the restaurant playing the football game. The seating reminded me of long park bench tables, big enough to fit large parties of 20 or 30. The craft beer bar is located on the left side of the restaurant while food is in the middle.

As far as food, Pizza Port offers premium gourmet pizzas. I originally wanted the Pizza SF but two friends had already ordered that, so I just randomly chose the featured month pizza, Teriyaki Chicken. It was just okay and I probably wouldn't get it again. The flavors didn't mesh well for me; carrots & broccoli inside a cheesy pizza. The pizza's are portioned generously, so if you're one person just go with the individual. There's also arcade games towards the back of the pizza restaurant. Pizza Port reminds me of an adult Shakey's. I will definitely come back but order the pizza I want regardless of who in the group gets it.</text>< pics>
None<//pics>

<Review>Don‚Äôt be fooled by the name, Pizza Port is a great pizza place as well, but even if they didn‚Äôt have pizza at all, they would be a pretty great bar and brewery. The outside patio section under some palm trees is awesome on nice days. The inside is huge with lots of long tables and great for big gatherings or small get togethers alike. The beer menu is huge as the Pizza Port brewing empire has several facilities. There are probably close to 3 dozen beers on tap across the range from blonde ales to porters. There are of course multiple hop forward IPAs that go great on a hot day. Even the malty wheat and ales are pretty delicious. The inside is a good place to catch sports as well with many TVs. The pizza isn‚Äôt bad either. This is your place to go to grab a pint after some time in the sun on the beach for sure.< /Review>< username>

4<//rate>
<Review>This is the quintessential surfer/craft beer hangout.  I think I literally saw Jeff Spicoli (if you're not old enough to know who that is, forget it).

On a serious note, the only thing that is not awesome about this place is the parking situation, but then again what can you expect in OB and thank the flying spaghetti monster that there are no soul sucking multi-story parking garages ruining the vibe that is OB.

I haven't been to the other Pizza Ports yet, but this one was fantastic albeit packed to the gills.  As you probably already know there is a plethora of home brewed craft beers, as well as plenty of guest taps.  Heavy on the D/I/PAs, in fact when I was there I think they had 7 IPAs and  3 or 4 DIPAs.  The beer line and the pizza line are separate and there are virtually no vegetarian pizza options, unless you roll your own (which you can if you want).

If I lived in OB (I'm not sure how this is possible anymore with real estate prices the way they are) I'd be there several times a week.< /Review><Pics>None< /Pics><response>None</response><Gmap_id>0x80deaa3a261cd2e3:0x3e89464c53bf352</Gmap_id></record>

< user>
110731487695307446140<//user>
<name>Lyndsi Winer< /name><Date>1409024064431< /Date><rate>4<//rate>< Review>
I can't particularly say I LOVE their pizza but it's ok.  Their atmosphere is great and their beer even better. They brew their own beer and dozens of types!  All SUPER SUPER awesome!  It's a place for craft beer aficionados!  Their staff is always happy to be there and happy to serve you and I very rarely can complain about them.  The pizza is ok, they have great specialty ingredients and the larger the pizza the better the crust I think.  Don't get a small if you don't like a lot of dough more like a hand tossed pan pizza.  The large is good and the lunch slices even better!  In fact they have the best lunch deal in town!  An amazing garden salad that me and my bf share and HUGE slices of pizza and soda for 5$ and if you want a beer its a 1$ more for regular beer and 2$ for stronger beers.  They always have a unique slice of the day accompanied with the choice also of pepperoni or cheese everyday and the slice with the salad is perfect!  I ate this almost daily when I worked across the street!  They are fast and the lunch is good and soooooo cheap!! They also have great salads!  The port salad is one of my favs!  It's all veggies and has so much in it that is unique you'll never miss the meat!  Roasted red peppers, blue cheese, spring mix, marinated portobellos and more!  It's to die for!!!<//Review>

<Name>Ezzy Crisan< /Name>< time>
1411330982366<//time>
< rate>
4</rate>
< Text>
We came here to hang out with friends, and this was a perfect spot. Great food, great beer selections, and great company!

We came here on a Sunday night, a night before Memorial day. It's been awhile, and I completely forgot how crazy busy it is in these Ocean Beach streets. We got luckily how easily we found a table fit for 8 people.  The place is always packed and  loud, however people are quite polite and respectful.

We tried out the honey beers, Carlsbad pizza, cajun bites, garlic bites and chicken wings.  The honey beers were a treat for me. I'm not much of a beer drinker, but the Honey beer is something I would keep ordering. It's light, tart, and a hint of honey for the after taste.  The carlsbad pizza intrigued me --with the mix of artichoke hearts, feta cheese, alfredo sauce and peppers. The pizza was a tasty creation. The saltiness and sweetness flavors worked well with the ingredients. Though, the chicken wings didn't impress me much. It was average. The cajun & garlic bites were ok. They were made in a pizza bread, and then cut into pieces, cajun ---with jalapenos & garlic -- stating the obvious, and put into a basket to share.

Whenever I'm in Ocean Beach, I'd be back here for the assortment of beers and pizza selections!< /Text>
